cs.IR, cs.LG, cs.CL, cs.SI, cs.CY 

This paper is likely to belong to the Information Retrieval (cs.IR) sub-category as it deals with recommender systems that assist users in navigating complex information spaces. The use of neural network architectures to learn rich distributed representations also suggests that it could belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category. The paper also mentions social annotation systems, which could place it in the Natural Language Processing (cs.CL) sub-category. Additionally, the use of multiple sources of data and the evaluation of the utility of the representations suggest that it could belong to the Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) sub-category. Finally, the paper's focus on collaborative filtering and user-item interactions could place it in the Cybersecurity (cs.CY) sub-category, which deals with protecting user data and privacy in online systems.
